Homework 3¶

In this homework we study Local Interpretable Model-agnostic Explanations (LIME). LIME focuses on explaining the model's predictions for individual instances rather than providing global understanding of the model on the entirety of the dataset. The method learns an interpretable model locally around the prediction. LIME first transforms input (observation of interest $x$) to the model into interpreatble feature space ($x'$). Then LIME creates training dataset by uniformly sampling from $x'$ and creating perturbed samples $z'$. Lastly local model behaviour is explaained by approximating it by an interpretable surrogate model (e.g. linear regression).

To explore LIME we selected dataset and models from HW1, which are described below.

Dataset¶

For our binary classification problem we selected QSAR-biodegradation dataset LINK, which has 17 features and 1055 rows. We changes classes labels from $\{1, 2\}$ to $\{0, 1\}$ for consistency with the procedure in HW1 (it was necessary to use BCELoss while training Neural Network Classifier). Class 0 has 699 instances and class 1 has $356$, thus this dataset's imbalance ratio is equal to $1.96$. The task is to discriminate ready (class $1$) and not ready (class $0$) biodegradable molecules based on molecular stucture descriptors.

Selecting observations for LIME¶

We set random seed for reproductibility and split dataset into training and validation datasets 80:20. We perform feature scaling using sklearn.preprocessing.StandardScaler. Then we sampled 4 observations for valiation datasets, 2 from each class.

The selected observations are presented in the table below.

Models¶

We selected sklearn.ensemble.GradientBoostingClassifierand sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier, which were one of better performing models based on analysis from HW1. To extend the scope of our analysis we included sklearn.linear_model.LinearRegression as an example of model with worse performance for comparison.

Since LIME is model-agnostic meaning that it does not depend on the model structure we can easily compare different models.

Performance¶

Selected models performed as shown in the table below.

recall precision f1 accuracy auc
GradientBoostingClassifier 0.898305 0.688312 0.779412 0.85782 0.92568
RandomForestClassifier 0.830508 0.720588 0.771654 0.862559 0.931813
LogisticRegression 0.762712 0.714286 0.737705 0.848341 0.899309

RandomForestClassifier performed the best with respect to the following metrics: recall, f1 and auc, while the best accuracy an precision was reached by GradientBoostingClassifier. However both models performed relatively similarly. Logistic regression performed worse than both tree methods with respect to all metrics except precision, where it placed second after RandomForestClassifier.

Results¶

1. Predictions for the selected observations¶

The predictions for the selected observations are presented below.

253 279 1002 626
TARGET 1 1 0 0
GradientBoostingClassifier 1 1 0 0
RandomForestClassifier 1 0 0 0
LogisticRegression 1 1 0 0

Even though generally RandomForestClassifier had the best performance here it did not classify observation 279 correctly. All other predictions for all models were correct.

2. Calculate the decomposition of the selected predictions with LIME.¶

We calculate the decomposition for selected predictions from GradientBoostingClassifier. Predictions 1002 and 626 correspond to target class 0, while predictions 253 and 279 correspond to target class 1.

3. Compare LIME for various observations in the dataset. How stable are these explanations?¶

Since LIME algorithm involves randomness we are going to check few random seeds: 0, 1, 2, 3.

Generally we observe stable behaviour for 2-3 most important variables for each observation depending on the chosen seed.

For both observations from class 0 (626 and 1002) three most important variables are V18, V22 and V1. While for observation 626 their order is the same independent of random seed, in the case of observation 1002 V22 and V1 switch beetween second and third place in the importance ranking.

Observations from class 1 did not have similar decomposition. While for observation 253 two most important variables were V18 and V22 as for observations for class 0, for observation 279 V22, V12, V39 were to 3 most important variables across all random seeds.

4. Compare LIME between at least two different models. Are there any systematic differences across many observations?¶

The main difference between the models is that the most important features for each observation have bigger contributions in explaining the prediction for LogisticRegression and GradientBoostingClassifier, than RandomForestClassifier, which might be the reason why it was the only model that predicted wrong class for observation 279. Also comparison between models confirms that observation 279 probably differs in an important way from other since it has rather different set of important variables for each model.

    explainer = dx.Explainer(model, X_test, y_test)
    # save explainer
    explainers[name] = explainer
